  "part2": {
    "strategicConcerns": [
      {
        "id": "sc-1",
        "outcomeId": "oo-1",
        "concern": "The National Queue Monitoring System (NQMS), built on Visual Basic 6 in 2009 and running exclusively on three Windows XP computers in the Monitoring Division, requires manual data entry from 847 monitored agencies. Each agency submits a monthly Excel file via email attachment, which NCWTR staff then re-encodes by hand into NQMS. The system crashes an average of 4.7 times per week, and the last full system restoration required 11 working days, three printed manuals, and a retired contractor who was contacted through his nephew.",
        "currentStrategy": "Manual paper-based re-encoding of Excel submissions from 847 monitored agencies into the NQMS. Monthly national report processing takes approximately three weeks, meaning published data is already outdated upon release. No API, no automated ingestion, and no disaster recovery beyond institutional memory.",
        "desiredStrategy": "Develop and deploy a cloud-based Unified Queue Monitoring Platform (UQMP) with a RESTful API for direct data submission by monitored agencies, real-time dashboards, automated report generation, and a mobile app for field validation officers — eliminating the need for manual re-encoding and the three Windows XP computers."
      },
      {
        "id": "sc-2",
        "outcomeId": "oo-1",
        "concern": "Despite its optimistic name, the Electronic Complaints Logging and Archival System (eCLAS) accepts citizen complaints primarily via fax — specifically, the only functioning fax machine in the NCR, shared with three other divisions and also used to order office supplies. Citizens who wish to file a complaint must download a PDF, print it, fill it out in triplicate (blue ink only), and mail or personally deliver it to the Central Office. Walk-in complainants join a queue to file complaints about excessive government waiting times. Online complaint submission was proposed in 2018, funded in 2020, procured in 2021, and is currently in User Acceptance Testing — with 7 UAT reports generated and 0 UAT cycles completed.",
        "currentStrategy": "Fax, mail, or walk-in complaint submission only. Complaints are scanned, printed for logging, then re-scanned into eCLAS by a data encoder. Average walk-in wait time is 47 minutes. Online channel has been 'coming soon' since 2019.",
        "desiredStrategy": "Launch the Citizen Feedback and Complaints Portal (CFCP) — a web and mobile platform allowing citizens to file complaints, track status in real time, and receive SMS notifications. Integration with UQMP will enable automatic cross-referencing of complaints against monitored agency queue data."
      },
      {
        "id": "sc-3",
        "outcomeId": "oo-2",
        "concern": "Each of the 17 regional offices maintains its own compliance tracking system — meaning 17 different Excel workbook formats, 17 different naming conventions, and 17 different definitions of 'compliant.' One regional office tracks compliance using a physical corkboard with color-coded index cards. Consolidating regional reports for the monthly national compliance index requires a dedicated staff member to manually reconcile data formats over four days, resulting in an average of 23 conflicting data points per report.",
        "currentStrategy": "17 separate, non-standardized Excel-based compliance tracking systems per regional office, with one corkboard outlier. Monthly reconciliation is entirely manual, time-consuming, and produces results of questionable accuracy. No automated roll-up mechanism exists.",
        "desiredStrategy": "Deploy the Regional Compliance Module of the UQMP, with standardized data fields, automated roll-up to the national dashboard, and mandatory digital submission replacing the corkboard system and the 17 competing Excel formats."
      },
      {
        "id": "sc-4",
        "outcomeId": "oo-3",
        "concern": "NCWTR's human resources data resides in a collection of 47 Microsoft Excel workbooks, the oldest dating to 2009 (Excel 2003 format, requiring a compatibility pack). The workbooks are stored on a shared network drive accessible only from the Central Office, making remote HR management impossible for all 17 regional offices. Employee records for three staff members hired between 2020 and 2022 were found in a folder labelled 'TEMPORARY — DO NOT DELETE' on a USB flash drive discovered in a desk drawer during an office clean-up drive. Three knowledge-transfer attempts have failed — the most recent trainee resigned mid-handover.",
        "currentStrategy": "HR management via 47 Microsoft Excel workbooks in a Central Office shared drive, managed by one person (Ms. Leonora 'Nora' Baluyot, NCWTR since 2007). No remote access, no standardization, and institutional knowledge that has resisted all documentation and succession efforts.",
        "desiredStrategy": "Procure and configure a modern, cloud-based Integrated Human Resources and Payroll System (iHRPS) integrated with CSC's HRMIS and DBM's eBudget systems, accessible to all regional and field offices — and finally resolving the Mystery of the Three USB-Recovered Employee Records."
      }
    ],
    "networkDiagrams": [],
    "networkDescription": "The NCWTR operates a deeply fragmented network infrastructure, inherited largely from its predecessor agency — the Presidential Committee on Queuing Excellence (PCQE), dissolved in 2018 after a 6-month queue formed at its building entrance.\n\nCENTRAL OFFICE (Quezon City): Connected via 1 Gbps fiber leased from a telecommunications provider. Hosts an on-premise server room containing four physical servers: two running Windows Server 2012 R2 (\"Production\" and \"Production-Backup,\" which has never been tested), one dedicated to the NQMS database, and one that has been \"under scheduled maintenance\" since March 2022. There is no disaster recovery site. The server room door bears a laminated sign: \"DO NOT ENTER unless you have filed Form NCWTR-IT-003-B (Rev. 2016) and obtained two signatures from the Division Chief.\"\n\nREGIONAL OFFICES (17 total): 5 regional offices have fiber connections ranging from 50–100 Mbps (NCR, Region III, Region VII, Region XI, and the one that submitted its connectivity upgrade request in the correct format). 9 regional offices operate on DSL connections at 5–10 Mbps — sufficient for email and not much else. 3 regional offices in geographically isolated areas share a single LTE pocket WiFi device among all staff, rotating custody based on who has the most urgent task.\n\nPROVINCIAL FIELD OFFICES (82 total): Access the NCWTR intranet via VPN tunnel routed through their regional office connection, resulting in effective speeds that make printing and faxing documents measurably faster than uploading them. File transfers of the monthly compliance report (average size: 4.2 MB) have been observed to take up to 25 minutes.\n\nINTERNAL NETWORK: The Central Office LAN uses a mix of Cat5e and Cat6 cabling installed at different points between 2008 and 2019. Network documentation exists in a hand-drawn diagram on Manila paper, last updated in 2017, now laminated and kept in the property officer's cabinet \"for safekeeping.\"",
